🌐 AWS Route 53 – Complete Beginner Guide:-

📖 Introduction
Imagine asking someone to remember this IP address every time they want to visit Amazon.
54.239.28.85. Instead, people simply type - amazon.com
How does the internet know where **amazon.com** is located?
This is where **DNS (Domain Name System)** comes into the picture.
AWS provides its own managed DNS service called **Amazon Route 53**.

Route 53 translates easy-to-remember **domain names** into **IP addresses**, allowing users to access applications without remembering complex numbers.

 🚀 What is Amazon Route 53?
Amazon Route 53 is a **highly available and scalable Domain Name System (DNS) web service** offered by Amazon Web Services (AWS).
It performs four major functions:
- 🌍 Domain Registration
- 🌐 DNS Management
- ❤️ Health Checks
- 🔄 Traffic Routing

Route 53 helps users connect to applications running on AWS or outside AWS using domain names.

❓ Why Do We Need Route 53?
Computers communicate using IP addresses. Humans remember names.
Imagine your application is running at 18.234.52.11 Would every customer remember this? Probably not. Instead, they type www.mywebsite.com Route 53 converts www.mywebsite.com into 18.234.52.11 and sends the user to the application.

