⚙️ How Route 53 Works

  Step 1 :- User enters www.example.com
  Step 2 :- Browser sends a DNS request.
  Step 3 :- The request reaches Amazon Route 53.
  Step 4 :- Route 53 checks the Hosted Zone.
  Step 5 :- It finds the matching DNS record.
  Step 6 :- Route 53 returns the destination IP address (or AWS resource such as an ALB).
  Step 7 :- The browser connects to the application.

🔥 Problems Solved by Route 53
 ✅ Problem 1 — Easy-to-Remember Domain Names
    Instead of 52.45.210.67 Users simply type google.com Route 53 resolves the domain name into an IP address.

 ✅ Problem 2 — Dynamic IP Addresses
    Suppose your application is behind an Application Load Balancer.

```
Internet
     │
     ▼
Application Load Balancer
     │
     ▼
EC2
```

If the Load Balancer is recreated, its IP address changes.Without DNS, users cannot access your application. 
Route 53 stores the DNS record instead of the IP.

```
myapp.com

↓

Application Load Balancer
```
Even if the Load Balancer's IP changes. users still use myapp.com without any changes.
  ✅ Problem 3 — High Availability

Suppose your application is deployed in two AWS Regions.
```
US-East-1

US-West-2
```
If one region becomes unavailable,Route 53 automatically redirects traffic to the healthy region.

 ✅ Problem 4 — Disaster Recovery
    If your primary application fails, Route 53 routes users to a backup application automatically.

 ✅ Problem 5 — Global Traffic Distribution
    Route 53 intelligently routes users based on
    - Geography
    - Latency
    - Health
    - Traffic Weight 
    making applications faster and more reliable.

📍 Where is Route 53 Used?
Amazon Route 53 is commonly used with
- Amazon EC2
- Application Load Balancer (ALB)
- Network Load Balancer (NLB)
- Amazon CloudFront
- Amazon API Gateway
- Amazon ECS
- Amazon EKS
- Elastic Beanstalk
- Amazon S3 Static Website Hosting
- Hybrid Cloud
- On-Premises Servers

 📅 When Should You Use Route 53?
Use Route 53 when you need to
- Register a domain
- Connect a domain to an application
- Point a domain to an ALB
- Host static websites
- Perform Health Checks
- Configure Disaster Recovery
- Perform Blue/Green Deployments
- Route traffic to different AWS Regions
- Route traffic based on latency
- Configure private DNS inside a VPC

🧩 Core Components
1️⃣ Domain Registration

You can purchase domains directly from AWS.

Example

```
mycompany.com
```

You can also transfer an existing domain from another registrar.

---
 2️⃣ Hosted Zone
A Hosted Zone stores all DNS records for a domain.

Example:- 
example.com

├── www
├── api
├── mail
└── dev

Hosted Zones are of two types
- Public Hosted Zone
- Private Hosted Zone

 3️⃣ DNS Records
DNS records tell Route 53 where to send traffic.
Common DNS records include

| Record | Purpose |
|---------|----------|
| A | Maps Domain → IPv4 Address |
| AAAA | Maps Domain → IPv6 Address |
| CNAME | Maps one domain to another |
| Alias | AWS resources like ALB, CloudFront, S3 |
| MX | Mail Servers |
| TXT | Verification & Security |
| NS | Name Servers |
| SOA | Start of Authority |

--
4️⃣ Health Checks ❤️
Health Checks continuously monitor your application.
If healthy ✔ Continue Routing Traffic

If unhealthy ❌ Stop Sending Traffic
Traffic automatically moves to another healthy endpoint.

🚦 Routing Policies

 1. Simple Routing

One domain
↓
One resource


 2. Weighted Routing
```
80% → Server A

20% → Server B
```
Useful for Canary Deployments.

 3. Latency Routing
Users connect to the AWS Region with the lowest latency.

 4. Failover Routing
Primary Server
↓
Fails
↓
Backup Server
```

Used for Disaster Recovery.

---
 5. Geolocation Routing
Users from India
↓
India Server

Users from USA
↓
USA Server
 6. Geoproximity Routing
Routes users based on geographic distance.
 7. Multi-Value Routing
Returns multiple healthy IP addresses.
Improves availability.

🌐 Public Hosted Zone vs Private Hosted Zone

| Public Hosted Zone | Private Hosted Zone |
|--------------------|---------------------|
| Internet Accessible | Only inside a VPC |
| Public Websites | Internal Applications |
